,"1571":"1571","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","1576":"1576","1587":"1587","1498":"1498","1530":"1530","June 1547":"juni 1547","10 December 1576":"10 december 1576","1609":"1609","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","Netherstowey,Somerset,England":"Nether Stowey, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Chew Magna, Somerset, England":"Chew Magna, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Andover, Hampshire, England":"Andover, Hampshire, England"},"en":{"1510–1609":"1510–1609","1535–Male":"1535–Deceased","1498–1547":"1498–1547","1530–1576":"1530–1576","1537–Female":"1537–Deceased","1538–Female":"1538–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","1571":"1571","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1510":"1510","1576":"1576","1587":"1587","1498":"1498","1530":"1530","June 1547":"June 1547","10 December 1576":"10 December 1576","1609":"1609","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","Netherstowey,Somerset,England":"Nether Stowey, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Chew Magna, Somerset, England":"Chew Magna, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Andover, Hampshire, England":"Andover, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mondy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Monday  . This surname is rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Monday","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Mundi</i>, <i>Mundy</i>, usually a pet form of male personal names ending in <i>-mund</i> or <i>-mond</i> (see   Mund  , and compare   Edmond  ,   Hammond  , and   Simmonds  ). Alternatively, and especially in northern and eastern England, the name might derive from Old Norse <i>Mundi</i>, a pet form of names like Old Norse <i>Agmundr</i>, Middle English <i>Agemund</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>Mone(n)day</i> ‘Monday’. It is possibly a name given to one born on that day or to a holder of <i>Mondayland</i>, land held on condition of working for the lord on Mondays."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":61,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":77,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":90,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.his